# WHY: init-system-helpers is required by the postinst script to call
# deb-systemd-helper for timer enable/disable. Although listed in the
# Debian "essential" set on some configurations, it is NOT guaranteed
# present on all Ubuntu 24.04 minimal installs and MUST be declared as
# a Depends. Version-pinning is omitted because we require any version
# that ships deb-systemd-helper (all released versions do).
sftp-jailer: depends-on-essential-package-without-using-version Depends: init-system-helpers

# WHY: sftp-jailer is a CGO_ENABLED=0 statically-linked binary by design.
# The REQUIREMENTS.md mandates a single static binary with no runtime
# dependencies beyond libc. Dynamic linking would break the deployment
# model (no Go runtime required on target). This is an intentional
# architectural decision, not an oversight.
sftp-jailer: statically-linked-binary [usr/bin/sftp-jailer]

# WHY: The maintainer scripts (postinst, prerm, postrm) use absolute paths
# for /usr/bin/deb-systemd-helper and /usr/bin/deb-systemd-invoke per
# the Debian systemd packaging guide. These helpers may not be in PATH
# in all invocation contexts (dpkg runs scripts with a minimal environ).
# Using absolute paths is the correct and safe approach for maintainer
# scripts that shell out to system helpers.
sftp-jailer: command-with-path-in-maintainer-script /usr/bin/deb-systemd-helper (in test syntax) [postinst:33]
sftp-jailer: command-with-path-in-maintainer-script /usr/bin/deb-systemd-helper (in test syntax) [postrm:55]
sftp-jailer: command-with-path-in-maintainer-script /usr/bin/deb-systemd-helper (in test syntax) [prerm:46]
sftp-jailer: command-with-path-in-maintainer-script /usr/bin/deb-systemd-invoke (in test syntax) [postinst:39]
sftp-jailer: command-with-path-in-maintainer-script /usr/bin/deb-systemd-invoke (in test syntax) [prerm:36]

# WHY: The prerm script calls sftp-jailer via its absolute path
# (/usr/bin/sftp-jailer) to run the purge-sshd-cleanup subcommand that
# backs up and removes the sshd drop-in before the binary is removed.
# The absolute path is correct — the script must target the installed binary,
# which may differ from any sftp-jailer in PATH. This is the correct
# pattern for prerm scripts that invoke the package's own binary.
sftp-jailer: command-with-path-in-maintainer-script /usr/bin/sftp-jailer (in test syntax) [prerm:63]
sftp-jailer: command-with-path-in-maintainer-script /usr/bin/sftp-jailer (plain script) [prerm:64]

# WHY: The postinst and prerm scripts call systemctl directly for operations
# that deb-systemd-helper cannot perform (e.g., systemctl daemon-reload,
# is-active checks). Per Debian systemd Policy §11.1 the preferred approach
# is deb-systemd-helper for enable/disable and direct systemctl for reload
# and status queries. The direct calls are guarded by
# "if [ -d /run/systemd/system ]" so they are safe on non-systemd systems.
sftp-jailer: maintainer-script-calls-systemctl [postinst:37]
sftp-jailer: maintainer-script-calls-systemctl [postinst:42]
sftp-jailer: maintainer-script-calls-systemctl [prerm:40]
sftp-jailer: maintainer-script-calls-systemctl [prerm:41]
sftp-jailer: maintainer-script-calls-systemctl [prerm:49]

# WHY: Architecture-Variant is a goreleaser-injected field used to track
# the Go arch/variant string (e.g., "amd64v1", "arm64v8.0"). It is not
# a standard Debian control field. goreleaser injects this for its own
# build artifact tracking; it does not affect package installation or
# functionality. Filed upstream: goreleaser/nfpm#999.
sftp-jailer: unknown-field Architecture-Variant

# WHY: The postinst script (DIST-04 SC3 closure, plan 05-07) calls
# /usr/bin/sftp-jailer init-db to initialize observations.db at the
# current schema version IMMEDIATELY at install time — before the
# systemd timer fires for the first time. The absolute path is correct
# for the same reason as the prerm purge-sshd-cleanup invocation: the
# script must target the installed binary, not whatever is in PATH.
# This is the canonical Debian pattern for postinst scripts that invoke
# the package's own binary to perform install-time initialization.
sftp-jailer: command-with-path-in-maintainer-script /usr/bin/sftp-jailer (in test syntax) [postinst:64]
sftp-jailer: command-with-path-in-maintainer-script /usr/bin/sftp-jailer (plain script) [postinst:64]
